'''Nostratic'''
# A hypothetical [[grouping]] usually consisting of [[Indo-European]], [[Uralic]], [[Altaic]], [[Chukchi-Kamchatkan]], [[Eskimo-Aleut]], [[Dravidian]], [[Elamite]], [[Sumerian]], [[Kartvelian]] and [[Afro-Asiatic]]. The [[Aegean]] languages have also been suggested by Allan R. Bomhard by his brief examination of a potentially close relationship between Etruscan and Indo-European in his book ''Indo-European and the Nostratic Hypothesis''. Joseph Greenberg had also added [[Ainu]] which is only accepted by a minority of Nostraticists. Since the term describes a theoretical grouping that remains conjectural due to a lack of clear evidence, the grouping lacks recognition among most comparative linguists today who prefer to treat [[Uralic]] and [[Altaic]] as seperate groups. Similarities noted between the two groups include the accusative case ending and pronominal stems.

